properties.description: Forming a discreet and private set of four interlocking houses set around an open courtyard, Walmer Yard is Peter Salter's only UK project. The houses now form the home of the Baylight Foundation.
properties.name: Walmer Yard

properties.description: Beautiful mausoleum in former Royal Navy cemetery, restored 1999 by the University of Greenwich. Many interesting plaques and grave stones.
properties.name: Devonport Mausoleum

properties.description: Livery hall first built in the 1530s, twice destroyed by fire and rebuilt (1666 & 1772). Late 19C facade and opulent Victorian interior.
properties.name: Drapers' Hall

properties.description: Barry Buildings: 1869. Grade II* listed. Palladian symmetrical plan, in terracotta and stone. Extensively refurbished 2017-2018. New Science Building 2016. Grimshaw Architects. RIBA National Award. Home to 'James Caird' boat.
properties.name: Dulwich College

properties.description: Architecturally distinguished and well-preserved, brick-built, Elizabethan Grade I listed manor house. Contains 17C wall-paintings, wood panelling, a charming walled garden and a fine Tudor turret. Many original features have been restored.
properties.name: Eastbury Manor House

properties.description: We're excited to open up our London campus as part of Open House Festival. Foster + Partners is a global studio for sustainable architecture, urbanism, engineering and design, founded by Norman Foster in 1967. With offices across the world, the practice works as a single entity that is both ethnically and culturally diverse, with people central to all our endeavours.
properties.name: Foster + Partners

properties.description: Part of Golden Lane Estate which was the first public housing to be listed. A maisonette with much of the original detailing and finishes.
properties.name: 4 Bayer House

properties.description: Grade II listed, built 1790. A central double door under a bracketed cornice hood, large sash windows with delicate glazing bars. Panelled interior. Curved entrance wall allowed carriages to turn in the narrow lane. Notable burial ground.
properties.name: Winchmore Hill Friends Meeting House & Burial Ground

properties.description: Delightful brick and tile building inspired by the famous 1688 Meeting House at Jordans in Buckinghamshire. A simple building in a tranquil setting, reflecting the Quakers' beliefs.
properties.name: Golders Green Quaker Meeting House

properties.description: Grade I listed Georgian garden building. Tribute to Shakespeare built in the Ionic style by actor David Garrick. Arcadian Thames-side setting in restored 18C gardens thought to be by Capability Brown.
properties.name: Garrick's Temple to Shakespeare, Hampton

properties.description: Exceptional example of the 'luxury cinema style' of the 1930s with outstanding Gothic interior by Theodore Komisarjevsky. The first Grade I listed cinema. Visitors must be aged over 18.
properties.name: Buzz Bingo Hall (former Granada Cinema)

properties.description: The City's seat of municipal government since 12C. Grade I listed, rare example of medieval civic architecture.
properties.name: Guildhall

properties.description: Hackney Empire is a grade II* listed building. The theatre was built as a music hall in 1901, designed by the architect Frank Matcham. It is now an exceptional variety theatre for the 21st century, serving the local community and beyond.
properties.name: Hackney Empire

properties.description: A sumptuous feast of Victorian stained glass & bold sacred sculpture in what Sir John Betjeman called the 'cathedral of the Arts and Crafts movement.' Work by William Morris, Edward Burne-Jones, William Blake- Richmond & Christopher Whall.
properties.name: Holy Trinity Church Sloane Square

properties.description: Grade II* listed tower with restored chapel remaining from Medieval parish church. Tour includes crypt, ringing chamber & main roof with excellent extensive views in all directions. Organised by Friends of Hornsey Church Tower.
properties.name: Tower and Churchyard of St Mary's Hornsey

properties.description: The home of Emery Walker, printer, antiquary and mentor to William Morris. A unique Arts and Crafts domestic interior.
properties.name: Emery Walker's House

properties.description: Built during the golden era of Camden public housing under Borough Architect Sydney Cook. Peter Tábori  studied with Ernő Goldfinger and worked with Denys Lasdun, and met Ken Adie when both were students at the Regent Street Polytechnic.
properties.name: 8 Stoneleigh Terrace (Highgate New Town, Stage 1)

properties.description: The World’s largest tidal mill. 5-storey, timber-framed, brick-clad timber watermill with four waterwheels, originally built 1776 to mill grain for distillery trade. Operational until 1940. On historic 3 Mills Site, Clock Mill adjacent.
properties.name: House Mill

properties.description: Grade I listed 1934 residential block of flats in Hampstead, designed by the Canadian modernist architect Wells Coates for clients Jack and Molly Pritchard. English Heritage blue plaque for Bauhaus masters Gropius, Breuer and Moholy-Nagy.
properties.name: Isokon Building (Lawn Road Flats)

properties.description:
Abbey Mills pumping station 'A', built by engineer Joseph Bazalgette, Edmund Cooper and architect Charles Driver. Built between 1865 and 1868 it is described as the cathedral of sewage.
Follow this link to book: https://bit.ly/abbeymills
properties.name: Abbey Mills Pumping Station

properties.description: Keats House is the beautiful Regency villa, where Romantic poet John Keats found inspiration, friendship and love. Today, it is a museum provided by the City of London Corporation for the benefit of London and the nation.
properties.name: Keats House

properties.description: Wren-designed building completed under the direction of Hawksmoor and Vanbrugh, 1698-1712. Original wood panelling, refurbished by Dannatt Johnson in 2001 for University of Greenwich.
properties.name: Old Royal Naval College - King William Court

properties.description: London's first fireproof building, built to house records of the Court of Chancery. Now renovated to house a fine university library.
properties.name: King's College London, The Maughan Library

properties.description: Grade II listed building. Substantial villa built in form of stone-faced baronial castle for the inventor of Bovril. An internal refurbishment is planned to convert it into a cultural and community space.
properties.name: Kingswood House

properties.description: The official residence of the Lord Mayor of the City of London, retaining its 18C character, with superb plasterwork and wood carving.
properties.name: Mansion House

properties.description: Grade I listed, late Georgian sugar warehouse now housing the Museum of London Docklands. Sensitively restored, the new multimedia displays coexist with the massive timber and brick structures of the original building.
properties.name: Museum of London Docklands

properties.description: Early Tudor Palace with Georgian reception rooms, Victorian Chapel, 13 acres of botanic gardens and walled garden.
properties.name: Fulham Palace

properties.description: Formerly boardroom of the 17C water house, the Oak Room is a fine late Renaissance room demonstrating the New River Company's wealth. Booking link: https://bit.ly/OakRooms
properties.name: Oak Room, New River Head

properties.description: A unique modern courtyard house making brilliant use of a restricted site. A retractable glass roof gives wonderful natural light and opens the house to the sky in dry weather.
properties.name: Paxton Locher House

properties.description: Described as 'the most significant church built after the WWII in Britain' - Brutalist, inclusive and influential signpost for future church design.
properties.name: St Paul's Bow Common

properties.description:
UPDATED: Open daily 10.30am-4pm. 
Guided tours 12.15pm & 1.15pm on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, Saturdays & Sundays, see below.
Home of the City of London's art collection, & remains of London's Roman Amphitheatre
properties.name: Guildhall Art Gallery

properties.description: Wren and Hawksmoor building, completed 1749 when Thomas Ripley built the pavilions facing the river. Highlights include council boardroom, grand staircase and restored Portland stonework. Refurbished in 2000 for University of Greenwich.
properties.name: Old Royal Naval College - Queen Anne Court

properties.description: Tudor timber-framed hunt standing/grandstand (1543),  Henry VIII Tudor food display. Gateway to 6,000 acres ancient Epping Forest, once royal hunting ground, protected since 1878 by City of London, Grade II*.  Epping Forest visitor Centre.
properties.name: Queen Elizabeth's Hunting Lodge

properties.description: Last major building on the site (1751). Original layout, timber panelling, barrel vaulting and Portland stone. Refurbished in 2000 by Dannatt Johnson for University of Greenwich.
properties.name: Old Royal Naval College - Queen Mary Court

properties.description: Built as a Whig gentleman's club and inspired by Italian Renaissance palaces. Lobby leads to an enclosed colonnaded courtyard with complementary glazed roof and tessellated floor. Tunnelled staircase leads to upper floor.
properties.name: Reform Club

properties.description: Grade II* listed Nonconformist chapel for 1,000 people. Described by Pevsner as 'one of the finest Nonconformist buildings in London'. Horseshoe plan, innovative cast-iron columns and tracery, restored as a centre for the performing arts.
properties.name: Round Chapel

properties.description: Grade II* listed building. Restored in 2012 to showcase magnificent Edwardian faience tile work, mosaic floor and other historic features in transformed modern surroundings that now provide the headquarters of the RCGP.
properties.name: Royal College of General Practitioners

properties.description:
Numbered amongst the UK's architectural glories and boasting 66 acres of beautiful grounds, the Royal Hospital Chelsea has been home to the iconic Army veteran community fondly known as the 'Chelsea Pensioners' since its foundation in 1692. 
The Great Hall and Chapel will not be accessible from 12.00-14.00 on Saturday 16th September due to an internal event. The remainder of the site will be open during this time. 

Visitors should note that filming will be taking place during the afternoon of Sunday 17th September. If you would like to be excluded from any filming, please let our staff and volunteers know on arrival at the site.
properties.name: Royal Hospital Chelsea, Home of the Chelsea Pensioners

properties.description: A very good example of Georgian/Adam architecture. Restoration 2012 of Great Room (James Barry paintings), Benjamin Franklin room. 2019, restoration and installation of 1754-2018 mural in the new Long Gallery.
properties.name: RSA (Royal Society for the encouragement of Arts, Manufactures and Commerce)

properties.description: A close of 13 self-built houses. Each is unique, built using method developed by Walter Segal, who led the project in the 1980s. Houses have been extended and renovated. Sustainable features including solar electric, water & space heating.
properties.name: Walter Segal Self-build Houses

properties.description: Once one of the grandest civic buildings in London and now a great arts venue, the Grade II listed Shoreditch Town Hall boasts many spaces, from the Victorian grandeur of the Assembly Hall to the intimate warren of untouched basement rooms.
properties.name: Shoreditch Town Hall

properties.description: Europe’s first traditional Hindu temple is a masterpiece of exquisite Indian craftsmanship. Using 5,000 tonnes of Italian and Indian marble and the finest Bulgarian limestone, it was hand-carved in India before being assembled in London.
properties.name: BAPS Shri Swaminarayan Mandir

properties.description:
The extraordinary home of architect Sir John Soane (1753-1837). 

https://www.soane.org/whats-on
properties.name: Sir John Soane's Museum

properties.description: Grade II listed 1881 former fire station with prominent watch tower and original fire doors.
properties.name: South London Theatre

properties.description: Grade I listed, remaining tower of medieval parish church, with working late 16C clock. New exhibition of Hackney's history. Extensive views from roof. (Organised by Hackney Historic Buildings Trust).
properties.name: St Augustine's Tower

properties.description: Grade I listed church dating from 1086, representing the architectural styles of many centuries, including Norman font and carved cats heads around Norman south doorway arch, Easter sepulchre and ancient yew tree in churchyard.
properties.name: St Peter & St Paul Harlington

properties.description: Temple Bar is a 350 year old gateway to the City of London, designed by Sir Christopher Wren. It formerly stood in Fleet Street, and was the last surviving gateway to the City of London.
properties.name: Temple Bar

properties.description: Medieval architecture meets Wren's refurbishments in this inspiring building, the Mother Church of the Common Law. The Magna Carta exhibit: has William Marshal and King John where they would have debated and agreed clauses of Magna Carta.
properties.name: The Temple Church

properties.description: Stunning regal building, the only surviving building from Whitehall Palace, one of the first examples of the principles of Palladianism being applied to an English building. Site of a set of magnificent ceiling paintings by Rubens.
properties.name: The Banqueting House

properties.description: Founded c1145 by the Abbess of Barking as a hospice for thirteen old and infirm men, the present building is 12C and 19C. Grade II* listed with many interesting monuments, including Burne-Jones windows.
properties.name: The Hospital Chapel of St Mary & St Thomas

properties.description: A spectacular Grade I listed building designed by famed architect John Nash. Built in 1831, these former townhouses have undergone refurbishments throughout their history. The building is now home to the UK's national science academy.
properties.name: The Royal Society

properties.description: One of the first garden suburbs in the world, 2-storey terraced cottages retaining decorative architectural features. LCC created 'housing of the working classes' role for architects' department under Riley, member of the Art Workers guild.
properties.name: Tower Gardens Garden Suburb

properties.description: The University of Westminster was one of the first polytechnics in the UK. Founded in 1838 as the Royal Polytechnic Institution, it was established to educate the working people of London, regardless of background or financial status.
properties.name: University of Westminster

properties.description: Grade II listed Town Hall clad in Portland Stone. The building incorporates Art Deco and Nordic Classicism styles, also being influenced by the work of local activist William Morris. Extensively refurbished in 2019 by Hawkins Brown.
properties.name: Waltham Forest Town Hall

properties.description: The recently automated impounding station controls the water level in the docks using the original Worthington Simpson pumps driven by Lancashire dynamo.
properties.name: West India Dock Impounding Station

properties.description: Grade I listed Georgian house, the only surviving home of Benjamin Franklin, retaining many original features including central staircase, lathing, 18th Century panelling, stoves, windows, fittings and beams.
properties.name: Benjamin Franklin House

properties.description: Rare example of a hollow post mill (1817). Grade II* listed, it now contains a museum depicting the history and development of windmills in Britain. Many working models, windmill machinery, equipment and tools.
properties.name: Wimbledon Windmill

properties.description: Mid-17C house, a scheduled ancient monument, with fine staircase and 18C additions.
properties.name: York House

properties.description: Grade II* listed church with ragstone tower, spire, good stained glass by Kempe and recently restored William Hill organ. A characteristic work of Scott. It is Gothic Revival in the style of the 13C.
properties.name: Christ Church

properties.description: Eccentric Edwardian church, Grade I listed. Described by Simon Jenkins as 'one of Lutyens' most distinctive creations'. Extensive 20C wall-paintings by Walter Starmer, memorial to horses of WWI. Local archives display.
properties.name: St Jude on the Hill

properties.description: Modern architecture church with large copper and lead roof and concrete, brick and stained glass external structure. Marble, wood and plaster interior and artwork by Sculptor Freda Pinto and Gerald Holtom.
properties.name: St Paul's, Newington

properties.description: The Old Palace was the official residence of the Bishops of Rochester. Present building dates from 1775, although there have been manor houses on the site since 10C.
properties.name: The Old Palace, Bromley Civic Centre (The Bishop's Palace)

properties.description: Tudor Manor House built for Sir William Compton in 1514, substantially altered in 17C, 18C & 19C. A museum since 1906 housing local history and community collections, archives, art & exhibitions of Bruce Castle, and Haringey area.
properties.name: Bruce Castle Museum

properties.description: Typical mid-Victorian stucco-fronted house built on a grassy hillside, extended in 1888 by Ernest Newton with William Morris redesigning the interiors. The library, formerly drawing room, has a unique William Morris hand-painted ceiling.
properties.name: Bullers Wood School for Girls

properties.description: Built in Neoclassical style for Hugh Morrison (1868-1931), this was the last mansion house of its kind to be built in London. The club, founded in 1891, moved to the premises in 1946.
properties.name: The Caledonian Club

properties.description: A unique ex-carpenters' workshop (1910), contained within a working police station. The workshop space now displays a history of Thames River Police.
properties.name: Thames River Police

properties.description: Grade I listed Norman brick-built church consisting of a nave and chancel. Tower at the west end. Gothic-style stone windows from the old church inserted into the present 1636 structure. Rare 17th Century glass was restored in 2020.
properties.name: St Lawrence Church, Morden

properties.description: Inigo Jones design 1640 at 59/60 LIF, copied  by 57/58  with portico and elliptical staircase added by Soane.  Refurbished by current occupiers, a barristers' chambers. Retains many original features, staircases, fireplaces and mouldings
properties.name: Garden Court Chambers

properties.description: The present brick tower windmill was built 1854 to replace a post mill destroyed by fire. Now renovated to near-working condition, it is the only surviving windmill in Croydon.
properties.name: Shirley Windmill

properties.description:
Built 1863 - a large corrugated iron chapel. Inside was transformed after the last war into a battleship by local sailors for Sea Cadets. 
It has decks, portholes a Bofors Gun and alter from the set of the 1964 film Becket.
properties.name: The Tin Tabernacle / Cambridge Hall

properties.description: Early 18C Grade II listed building incorporating plunge bath with Delft tiles, orangery, saloon and pump chamber with part-restored water wheel. Hermitage and sham bridge in grounds.
properties.name: Carshalton Water Tower and Historic Gardens

properties.description: London's main tourist information centre is clad in a specially manufactured system of 220 pre-finished stainless steel panels. The subtly reflective surface provides a striking counterpoint to St Paul's.
properties.name: City Information Centre

properties.description: Ruskinian walk from RIBA award-winning Chiswick Business Park, Gunnersbury Triangle Nature Reserve through South Acton Estate, birthplace of artist Patrick Caulfield; Woodlands Park Ice House; to home of Wm Willett, of Daylight Saving Time
properties.name: A Ruskinian Walk Through Shared Heritage

properties.description: Completed in 1895, Two Temple Place is a dazzling neo-Gothic gem on the Victoria Embankment, designed by gothic revivalist architect, John Loughborough Pearson, & commissioned by & built for William Waldorf Astor, as his estate office.
properties.name: Two Temple Place

properties.description: A guided walk, Wanstead Station to The Temple, Wanstead Park, taking in Wanstead's history and architectural heritage .The walk finishes at The Temple and will include an optional private tour of its displays.
properties.name: Wanstead Heritage Walk

properties.description: Grade II listed church with fine collection of Pre-Raphaelite stained glass windows by Morris & Co. including Burne Jones and Rossetti. Wall paintings. Mosaic reredos. Minchenden Oak  - ancient pollarded oak more than 800 years old.
properties.name: Christ Church Southgate and the Minchenden Oak Garden

properties.description: One of only two primary schools designed by Erno Goldfinger using a pre-cast concrete system - an important modernist building. The building is Grade II* listed and has a fine top-lit mural in the foyer, commissioned by Goldfinger and designed and painted by Gordon Cullen, recently re-restored.  The schoolkeeper's cottage has recently been refurbished and brought into the daily life of the school.
properties.name: Greenside Primary School

properties.description: Medieval Parish Church, 15C, enlarged & rebuilt in 19C. Shingle spire 1857, by Wollaston. Chancel by Ferrey, lengthened with East wall by Bodley & Garner. Scadbury Chapel (Walsingham tombs), with rood screen. Clock by Dent, 1858.
properties.name: St Nicholas Church, Chislehurst

properties.description: Former Midland Grand Hotel, now St Pancras Renaissance Hotel and Chambers apartments. Includes hotel lobby and clock tower.
properties.name: St Pancras Chambers and Clock Tower

properties.description: The building features a limestone exterior designed to 'complement but not mimic' the surrounding historical architecture, whilst behind the façade is a 4-storey composition of steel, glass and exposed concrete.
properties.name: University of Greenwich, Stockwell Street

properties.description: One of a pair of modern houses on a sensitive site in a conservation area. A triple-height staircase atrium brings light into the heart of the house and ground floor areas open onto courtyard gardens on three sides.
properties.name: Springbank

properties.description: St Anne's Limehouse has been described as 'the finest parish church in England.' Designed by Nicholas Hawksmoor, it is Grade I listed and one of the Major Churches in the Church of England. It is home to a thriving Christian congregation.
properties.name: St Anne's Church, Limehouse

properties.description: The NOW Gallery is an art space - contained within two curved glass pavilions linked by a patinated brass-edged canopy - which defines the southern edge of Peninsula Square and acts as a gateway to the south, the cable car and Central Park.
properties.name: NOW Gallery : Design District

properties.description: Tree-lined housing estate on the ridge of Central Hill & Crystal Palace, incorporating open spaces, views over London, gardens and sense of community. Rosemary Stjernstedt Ted Hollamby Adrian Sansom, Lambeth Borough Architects 1963.
properties.name: Central Hill Estate

properties.description: Baroque palace built for King William III and Mary II. The original Tudor towers and chimneys were replaced by grand and elegant exteriors that dominate the buildings today.
properties.name: Royal School of Needlework

properties.description: Modernist extension to Hackney's German Hospital, closed 1987 and converted into flats in 1999.
properties.name: Bruno Court, The German Hospital

properties.description: The operational factory of Kaymet, a maker of trays and trolleys since 1947. A hidden 1950s building with a small yard, originally a printing works. It is brick built, with clear-storey glazing and tubular truss north-light main shed roof.
properties.name: Kaymet Factory

properties.description: A makerspace offering open access to a fully equipped wood and metal workshop with bench space, tools and machinery. Includes education space, community café and 40 studios for creative businesses.
properties.name: Blackhorse Workshop

properties.description: A double-height ark floats above a masonry base & entrance footbridge.  Off the elevated living area a smokers' balcony overlooks the lush garden below. Above, semi circular terrace and winter garden nestles within the wooded surrounds.
properties.name: 6 Wood Lane

properties.description:
Victorian Potting sheds converted to artists' studios set within the grounds of Grade II listed Cannizaro Park.
The eight resident artists will be displaying their work during the festival at these unique studios.
properties.name: Cannizaro Studios

properties.description: A walk around the streets that the young Herbert George Wells knew when he was growing up and wrote about in his autobiography. You will get a flavour of Bromley in its Victorian heyday - all in the words of the author of the 'Time Machine'
properties.name: HG Wells' Bromley - in his own words

properties.description: One of the finest examples of Georgian architecture. It has been hardly altered since built. The church is a rectangular building of Portland stone, with a projecting chancel. Two external walls were restored in 2019. Grade I listed
properties.name: St Mary The Virgin Wanstead

properties.description: The Gilbert & George Centre was originally established as a registered charity by the artist in 2009 with the objective to advance the education of the public in the arts, and generally to advance the arts, architecture, heritage and culture for the benefit of the public.
properties.name: The Gilbert & George Centre

properties.description: Epping Forest Visitor Centre at Chingford, The View, a visitor centre and museum, was created from an early 20C stable complex. Enjoy its Forest viewing balcony, exhibitions and unique status as gateway into 6000 acres of Forest trails.
properties.name: Epping Forest Visitor Centre at Chingford, The View

properties.description: The Estorick Collection is housed in a beautiful Georgian building previously known as Northampton Lodge. Today, the museum comprises six galleries over three floors, as well as a library, offices, a café and bookshop.
properties.name: Estorick Collection of Modern Italian Art

properties.description: London’s 2012 Games provided a catalyst for regeneration in the Lower Lea Valley. Guided by the Legacy Masterplan, thousands of new homes and jobs are now being created, stitching together existing communities across the former floodplain.
properties.name: Olympic Legacy Masterplan

properties.description: James Maltby Bignall (1827-1885) worked in the practice of Sir George Gilbert Scott, the architect of St Pancras Station. The style of St Michael's is late Gothic Revival, in its size and height reminiscent of Northern European churches.
properties.name: St Michael and All Angels Church

properties.description: Large, late 17C Grade II* listed house with fine staircase and Venetian window and Georgian additions, used as a family dwelling until the early 1900s. Reopened to the public in Feb 2009 following extensive restoration works.
properties.name: Valentines Mansion & Gardens

properties.description: Grade II* listed church dating from 12C with Medieval, Tudor, Georgian & Victorian features. 16C Tower. Church refurbishment and new extension in progress in 2022. Over 1300 monuments with four Grade II listed tombs in churchyard.
properties.name: St. Mary's Church, Walthamstow Village

properties.description: Architecture and art produced in an unmodified street of 56 houses, railway arch studios, and private galleries between 1974 and 2022. Beck Rd is an iconic artist haven and its residents key contributors to UK art history.
properties.name: ‘OPEN’ Beyond Beck Road (part II)

properties.description: Originally St, Mary's Infants School, later as Holy Innocents' National School until 1934. It then became derelict until 1981 when it became headquarters of the Hornsey Historical Society in 1981 after refurbishment.
properties.name: The Old Schoolhouse

properties.description: The carefully renovated Van Gogh House seeks to share its story and inspire a new generation of artists through Van Gogh’s London story. The house curates a dynamic programme of events anchored in the artist’s practice and local heritage.
properties.name: Van Gogh House London

properties.description: Unit used as an art studio in a small industrial estate.
properties.name: Cut Glass Studio Ltd, Tottenham Hale

properties.description: Terrace of five three-storey houses and a studio incorporating a sequence of communal and private spaces. Influential prototype for Camden social housing developments of the 1960s and 70s.
properties.name: Winscombe Street 1960s terrace

properties.description: Unit 1.20 is one of 25 workshop and retail units in Oxo Tower Wharf and overlooks the courtyard towards the Bargehouse building from the first floor walkway. It is a multi-purpose space used as a workshop, showroom and teaching space.
properties.name: 1.20 Oxo Tower Wharf

properties.description: A low energy refurbishment of an Edwardian house, with rear extension and loft conversion. Wood fibre insulation, MVHR, airtightness layer, triple glazing, timber structure and low embodied energy materials.
properties.name: 1 Halliwick Road

properties.description: A rare example of a large purpose built metropolitan working men’s club with over 100 years of history. A once dignified building, revival Queen Anne style in the late-Victorian period, Grade II listed in 2019.
properties.name: The Mildmay Club

properties.description: Taylor Court and Chatto Court, together with Wilmott Court, form a pair of award-winning mixed-tenure housing, accommodating 45 new homes and commissioned by the Hackney Council on two sites at the edge of the post-war Frampton Park Estate.
properties.name: Taylor & Chatto Courts and Wilmott Court, Frampton Park Estate

properties.description: Grade ll listed Oxford Movement Anglican church built 1887-88. Historic England describe the exterior as ‘quirky and aggressive’ but the  interior is ‘very spare and elegant, the proportions subtly adjusted’. Elevated choir and sanctuary.
properties.name: Holy Cross Church, Cromer Street

properties.description: Little Angel Theatre was converted from a derelict temperance hall in 1961 and has been showcasing puppetry performances ever since. It is London's only purpose-built puppet theatre, due to the existence of its marionette bridge.
properties.name: Little Angel Theatre

properties.description: A grand neo-classical building of 1871 with impressive interior, built as New Court Congregational Chapel. Home to a Hunter pipe organ, installed as a WW1 memorial and recently restored with National Lottery Heritage Fund support.
properties.name: RC Church of St Mellitus

properties.description: Chicago Booth's London campus combines the best of old and new. Located near St. Paul's, the campus features more than 50 pieces of contemporary art and houses our Executive MBA Programme Europe, Executive Education, and conference centre.
properties.name: University of Chicago Booth School of Business

properties.description: This Grade I Mansion House, close to St Paul's Cathedral was designed by Edward Woodroofe in 1669 and completed in 1673.  The residence of successive Deans of St Pauls until the 1970's today it is the office to the Bishop of London
properties.name: The Old Deanery

properties.description:
In 1666, the conflagration devastated most of the City, thousands of houses, many churches and St Paul's Cathedral destroyed. Christopher Wren played a major role in rebuilding the City. 
Free walks led by City of London Guides
properties.name: The Great Fire of London

properties.description:
On this walk we will see many historic & modern buildings. see different architecture styles having regard to the environment and sustainability, and hear about famous architects, past and present.

Free walks led by City of London Guides
properties.name: Historic & Modern Buildings in the City

properties.description:
On this walk we shall discover some of the livery companies, learn about their ancient traditions and ceremonies, which are repeated every year. Also hear about  their important role in the City.
Free walks led by City of London Guides
properties.name: Ancient Livery Companies in the City of London

properties.description:
Join us for an interesting and informative walk around Surbiton with our experienced guide. Find out why Surbiton was called the Queen of the suburbs and plenty more. 

Visit our website: https://www.kingstontourguides.org.uk/
properties.name: Surbiton Queen of the Suburbs

properties.description: C3 is home to Bureau, a members club at the heart of Design District. Its undulating white facade creates informal pockets of space on the interior, ideal for flexible working models.
properties.name: C3 : Bureau Design at District

properties.description: The redevelopment of a former furniture warehouse in Hackney. Using CLT and glulam, the existing building has been extended to include a new building over the yard as well as a new office space on the top floor of the main building.
properties.name: Chart Street Studios

properties.description: This new sundial faces East so gets only morning sun. It is 10 m. square and was opened in 2021, and is publicly accessible 24/7
properties.name: Fleet Street Heritage Information Project and Sundial

properties.description: A tour of one of the largest and best preserved early Victorian squares and gardens in London, also with a magnificent and original public library of 1906, which shows Byzantine and Art Nouveau influences, and a remarkable Gothic church.
properties.name: Thornhill Square

properties.description:
UPDATED: Open daily 10.30am-4pm Closed Mon 19 September.
Combined guided tours of Amphitheatre and Guildhall Art Gallery at 12.15pm & 1.15pm on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, Saturdays & Sundays.
The capital’s only known Roman Amphitheatre
properties.name: London's Roman Amphitheatre

properties.description: Hear about some of the initiatives under way in the Tottenham High Street Heritage Action Zone (High Street HAZ). LB Haringey and the Tottenham Civic Society host a tour uncovering the rich heritage of this bustling, multicultural area.
properties.name: Heritage on the High Road (High Street HAZ)

properties.description: Our timber frame building was designed by Matrix Feminist Design Co-Operative, and built by women. It represents our community's history of activism-the same ethos that transformed our site from dereliction, into a thriving community garden
properties.name: Walworth Garden

properties.description: A 1960s former office block that has been transformed into a vibrant cultural hub showcasing the best of contemporary African culture and heritage. This project is supported by the Mayor of London.
properties.name: The Africa Centre

properties.description: Two York stone Chapels are linked by a carriage arch built from Kentish Ragstone. The exterior is symmetrical and sturdy but the interior is a light stained glass spacious sanctuary with original features that make you step back in time.
properties.name: The Chapel in Tottenham Cemetery

properties.description: Two-Up Two-Down House is a reworking of a Victorian mid terrace by architects Khan Bonshek. They use imaginative spatial devices to maximise the limited floor area. Double height volumes & blurring of rooms combine to create space & light.
